<!-- %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%	K   %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% -->
<p><alert>K</alert></p>
<p>
	<dl>
		<li>
				<title>Kernel</title>
			<p>
				The <em>kernel</em> of a linear transformation <m>T:V\rightarrow W</m> is the set of all <m>\vec{v}\in V</m> such that <m>T(\vec{v})=\vec{0}</m> in <m>W</m>. We abbreviate the kernel of <m>T</m> by <m>ker(T)</m>.  The kernel of a transformation is also known as the <em>null space</em>.
			</p>
		</li>
	</dl>
</p>

<!-- %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%	L   %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% -->
<p><alert>L</alert></p>
<p>
	<dl>
		<li>
				<title>Linearly Independent Vectors</title>
			<p>
				<em>Linearly independent vectors</em><idx><h>vector</h><h>linearly independent</h></idx> is a ... are called <em>linearly dependent</em><idx><h>vector</h><h>linearly dependent</h></idx>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
				<title>Linear Transformation</title>
			<p>
				A <em>linear transformation</em><idx><h>linear transformation</h></idx> is a map, <m>T</m>, from a vector space <m>V</m>, called the domain, to a vector space <m>W</m>,called the codomain, with the following properties:
				<ol>
					<li><m>T(\vec{u}+\vec{v})=T(\vec{u})+T(\vec{v})</m> for all <m>\vec{u},\vec{v}\in V, and </m></li>
					<li><m>T(c\vec{v})=cT(\vec{v})</m> for all scalars <m>c</m> and vectors <m>\vec{v}\in V</m>.</li>
				</ol>
			</p>
		</li>
	</dl>
</p>

<!-- %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%	M   %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% -->
<p><alert>M</alert></p>
<p>
	<dl>
		<li>
				<title>Matrix</title>
			<p>
				A <em>matrix</em><idx><h>matrix</h></idx> is a two dimensional array of numbers.  If the dimensions are given as <m>m\times n</m> then there are <m>m</m> rows and <m>n</m> columns in the array.
				E.g.
				<me>
					\left(
						\begin{array}{rr} 
							4 \amp 3\\
							2 \amp 5
						\end{array}
					\right)
				</me>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
				<title>Matrix Equation</title>
			<p>
				A <em>matrix equation</em><idx><h>matrix</h><h>equation</h></idx> is a ...
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
				<title>Matrix of a Transformation</title>
			<p>
				If <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^m</m> is a linear transformation, then the <em>matrix of the transformation</em> is the unique matrix <m>A</m> of dimension <m>m\times n</m> such that <me>T(\vec{x})=A\vec{x}\ \mbox{for all}\ x\in\mathbb{R}^n.</me>  
				If <m>\vec{e}_i</m> is the <m>i^{th}</m> column of the identity matrix over <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then the <m>i^{th}</m> column of <m>A</m> equals <m>T(\vec{e}_i)</m>.
			</p>
		</li>
	</dl>
</p>
